Step-by-step 

Prepare environment

Install dependencies:

pip install pillow

(Optional) Ensure Pillow has ImageCms by installing LCMS system libraries then reinstalling Pillow.

2. Prepare folders

Create an input folder and place your .jpg/.jpeg files there:
mkdir images
Copy images into images/.

3. Save the script

Save the code above to jpg_to_glb_srgb_full.py in the project folder.

4. (Optional) Obtain an sRGB ICC profile

If you have special color workflow requirements, download an sRGB ICC file (e.g., sRGB.icc) or use a system one. This is rarely required; ImageCms.createProfile("sRGB") often suffices.

5. Run the script

Basic:
python jpg_to_glb_srgb_full.py images out_glb

With explicit ICC:
python jpg_to_glb_srgb_full.py images out_glb /path/to/sRGB.icc

6.Verify output

Inspect out_glb/ — there should be one .glb per input image.

Open a few in a viewer:
https://gltf-viewer.donmccurdy.com/
https://sandbox.babylonjs.com/

7. If colors look off

Ensure images are already in sRGB or pass an ICC profile.
Confirm viewers apply sRGB as expected — differing tone mapping or lighting in viewers can change appearance.
If EXIF orientation was not applied earlier, the script applies it; verify rotated images are correct.


8.Notes, caveats and further options

Preserving exact original bytes: The script re-encodes to JPEG after orientation/profile conversion to embed the final pixel data. If you want to avoid re-encoding (preserve original compressed bytes), you'd need to:
Apply rotation to byte stream yourself (harder), or
Rotate pixels and reuse original compression (not generally possible without re-encoding).
Transparency: JPEG has no alpha. Use PNG sources if you need transparency, adjust MIME to "image/png", and set "alphaMode": "BLEND" and material["doubleSided"]=True as needed.
Multiple images in one GLB: If you prefer a single GLB containing all images as separate planes, the script can be adapted to create multiple meshes, materials, and nodes in one scene.
Large images: Embedding large images will create large GLB files. Consider resizing ahead of embedding (use Pillow .resize()), or using lower JPEG quality.
Index size limits: This script uses 16-bit indices (UNSIGNED_SHORT). For meshes with >65535 vertices you must use 32-bit indices.

